\details{
\strong{Computation.} Ht is a closed form -- the Frechet / rearrangement collapse that
reduces the transposed Mokken scalability to a per-respondent covariance ratio in
\code{O(n * p)} time and memory (one pass plus a per-respondent sort), without
materialising the n-by-n person matrix. Reverse-keyed items (\code{items$reverse_keyed})
are reverse-scored first with \code{(min + max) - x} (\code{min} defaults to \code{1}). Only
reverse-keyed items need a \code{max}; heterogeneous category counts are accepted with
no ceiling, so wide scales (11-point, 0-100, mixed-width) score directly.

\strong{Cutoff.} By default the cutoff is the \code{fpr} quantile of the observed scores (5th
percentile); respondents at or below it are flagged. This ranking convention flags
at least \code{fpr} of respondents, not a calibrated false-positive rate. Setting
\code{method = "mc_null"} instead resolves the cutoff against a model-conforming
simulated null -- the same mechanism \code{\link[=cier_gnormed]{cier_gnormed()}} uses (a sum-score-conditional
resample of the scored block, excluding constant vectors), scored by the Ht kernel
and summarised by the lower-tail bootstrap quantile at level \code{fpr}; its flag rate
is not pinned at \code{fpr}. With \code{seed = NULL} the null cutoff and flags vary run to
run; pass an integer \code{seed} to fix them (applied locally). \code{fpr} and \code{cutoff} (an
absolute value in \verb{[-1, 1]}) are mutually exclusive, and a literal \code{cutoff}
overrides \code{method} (then \code{seed} is unused).

\strong{Abstention.} Computed on complete cases: any missing cell excludes a respondent
(\code{value} and \code{flagged} are \code{NA}). A straightliner (fully-answered zero-variance row)
is structurally unscalable, so it too abstains -- the complement of \code{\link[=cier_gnormed]{cier_gnormed()}},
which scores straightliners. If fewer than two respondents are complete, or fewer
than two vary, every \code{value} is \code{NA}, a warning is emitted, and no one is flagged.
}
